Section section_02 (Chars 8316–12794):
Section Summary: The Egyptian king, Amenophis IV, later known as Akhenaten, introduced a new monotheistic religion that worshipped the sun disk, Aten, as the chief deity. He attempted to reform the traditional Egyptian religion, but faced resistance from the powerful priests of Amon in Thebes, leading to open strife and the eventual relocation of the court to a new city, Akhet-Aten. The king and his officials adopted new names and titles to reflect their allegiance to the Aten, but the new doctrine was not widely accepted, especially among foreign officials in Syria and Palestine. The Aten dogma represented a significant shift in religious thought, emphasizing natural phenomena over mythology, and was characterized by a more personal and spontaneous expression of devotion. The king rewarded officials who accepted the new doctrine, granting them honors and important positions, such as Ai, who received golden honors and served as a royal scribe and ambassador.
